replyContent: Leaf has 3 CAN busses in the OBDII connector. LeafSpy only connect to the CAR CAN. The A/V CAN is not used but it sounds like your old OBDII adapter was affecting the A/V CAN. I would suggest trying a newer OBDII Adapter. If LeafSpy actually had this effect Nissan would have contacted me long ago. I have worked with Nissan before (not the dealer).

content: I used to love this app but on cm12.1 I am constantly getting a bts read socket error. Has happened on multiple ROMs.
replyContent: Yes, Bluetooth on CM is a problem. I have traced this and found that CM does not pass all the control data through the BT stack. Try a WiFi OBDII adapter or (not likely you would do) reload the original OS that came with your device. You could also get a cheap $20 device just for the app.

content: This app will tell you.

I got this app mainly to check my battery and found it not very accurate,  more like pot luck as to the reading you will get. It  jumped from 97% to  89% back 100% and back to 89% over the period I tested. So a waste of  money if you want it for battery checks. UPDATE: it's the SOH and telling me it does not happen is simply not true. I know others who have had same experience.
replyContent:
SOH comes directly from the Leaf and does not jump around. It changes very very slowly.  It normally takes months to change 1%.

The only time it would go up is if you have taken your Leaf in for a firmware update and Nissan reset the SOH back to 100%. I that case it might change (drop) more quickly until it reached its previous value.
